# Hard Constraints (always)

These rules override convenience habits. If anything else conflicts, follow this file.

## 1) Commit preparation (mandatory gate)

When the user asks to prepare a commit (e.g. 准备commit, 准备提交, 帮我准备commit, **我要commit**, 写提交信息, commit message, summarize for commit):

- **Prepare ≠ execute:** phrases like 准备/我要 commit mean **draft message + wait for approval**, not immediate `git commit`. See `git-commit-mentor` skill.
- Inspect staged/unstaged changes first; draft from **actual** diffs only.
- Use **Conventional Commits** for the subject: `type(scope): summary`. Summary = concrete work, not Feature/Slice IDs.
- Run **Doc DoD** checks per `git-commit-mentor` when the change is feature/design/bug-driven.
- Present the **full draft** and **wait for explicit approval** before `git add` / `git commit`.
- **NEVER** run `git commit` (or push) unless the user clearly approves that draft **and** asks to execute.
- If the user only wanted a message draft, stop after the draft unless they then ask to commit.

## 2) Gameplay design doc (user-owned)

- **Authoritative gameplay design:** `docs/design/Overview.md` + `docs/design/systems/*.md` (git-tracked).
- **Default: read-only for agents** — do not edit unless the user **explicitly** requests (e.g. 帮我在 effects.md 里改公式).
- Engineering collaboration lives in `docs/ai/`; do not duplicate gameplay prose there.
- Full policy: `.cursor/rules/design-doc-governance.mdc`, `docs/design/DESIGN_DOC_GOVERNANCE.md`.

## 3) TypeScript implementation (when code exists)

When writing or editing `.ts` / `.tsx`:

- **`packages/core`:** pure rules engine — no DOM, no React, no Node-only I/O in core logic.
- **Effects:** data-driven (JSON + interpreter/registry); avoid hardcoding per-card logic in core.
- **RNG:** seeded and serializable for reproducible tests and agent play.
- **Hosts** (`cli`, `editor`, `ui`): may use Node/DOM; depend on `core`, not the reverse.
- **Coding habits:** reuse over duplicate; delete superseded code in the same change; touch-it-then-tidy transitional paths — see `.cursor/rules/implementation-discipline.mdc`.

## 4) Context recovery (re-apply this rule)

**Re-read and silently re-apply sections 1–3** (and `implementation-discipline.mdc`) at the start of your reply when any of these is true:

- New Cursor session or thread, or conversation was **summarized / compressed**.
- User says **re-bootstrap**, **对齐约束**, or asks to realign with project rules.
- Resuming after a long tool-heavy stretch before a **non-trivial code change** or **commit-related** action.
- Unsure whether commit-approval or design-doc rules still apply.

After recovery: do not repeat the full rule text unless the user asks; behave according to it.
